[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Creating cartoons with AI has never been easier. The tools are so advanced now that creating consistent characters, voices, and locations is a walk in the park, but only if you\'re using the right methods. I\'m Jack. I\'ve spent over a'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'decade creating visual effects for many of the biggest brands on the planet. And now I\'m using AI to reinvent creative workflows. We\'ve all dreamed of building our own cartoon show, then realized how complex it really is. You need to be'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'able to draw, understand animation, and even pay for voice actors. But thanks to AI, a single creator can now control every step of the process. And this is bigger than just saving money. Because'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'instead of hiring an entire team, now you\'re in the driving seat as the writer, director, and animator all rolled into one. I\'ll teach you every step of the process, including all the tips and tricks other creators aren\'t'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'telling you. So, as soon as you finish this video, you can start building your very own cartoon from scratch. And if you do enjoy today\'s content, be sure to whack a like on there for me and consider subscribing. All right, let\'s'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'get into it. So, straight off the bat, I want to be clear that this workflow is geared towards building an entire cartoon show rather than just isolated scenes, which I think is actually pretty easy. Now, we\'re focusing on building up'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a really strong set of repeatable characters, locations, and voices which can be used to make multiple episodes and all feel consistent and part of the same world. And make sure you stick'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'around until the end of the video because I\'ll show you how you can actually use your own voice in your video generations. And this is pretty groundbreaking in my view and something I don\'t see enough people talking about.'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'The first step of the process and a part which I think is incredibly important is building up a strong set of references. So for this I suggest you head over to sites like Pinterest. You could also go'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'across to Midjourney as well. And what you\'re looking for is cartoon styles that really appeal to you. They have to really resonate with you. And anytime you stumble upon a reference that you'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'really like, you want to go ahead and save it. Ultimately, the idea here is that you come away with an entire folder filled with amazing yet varied examples of different cartoon styles. And this'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'will inform you when you\'re trying to settle on a style of your own. So, once you\'ve collected that set of references, we\'re ready to actually start generating the visuals for our own cartoon show.'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'And to do that, we\'re over on Higsfield AI. If you guys did want to go ahead and follow along, you\'ll find a link down below in the description. So, you can see here I have this really wide array of different cartoon versions of myself.'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'This is where I\'m trying to figure out what vibe I want to go for and what\'s going to work for my specific show. So, let me show you how to do this. You first want to go ahead and drop in some'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'reference images of yourself or the character that you\'re trying to create alongside one of those star references that you liked the look of. Obviously, it\'s very useful to test out multiple'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'variations exactly like I did. And if you don\'t want to use your own likeness, that\'s absolutely fine. You can just skip on uploading the image references that I put up here. And we tie all of'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'this together with a very simple prompt. Now, all of my prompts and materials I use for this project will be available on my school community for completely free. Link for that down below in the'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'description. Now, you\'ll see that this prompt has been written to describe me. All you need to do is use this as a framework and put in your own description. Whether you want to recreate yourself as a cartoon character or if you\'re just describing an entirely'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'new character, you don\'t want to look anything like you. So, initially we\'re saying show the bearded man in the attached cartoon style and then I\'m describing my build. You of course want to leave in this front part here and'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'just swap in man, woman, cat, dog, whatever you want. I\'ve then added to the end here just a little bit more description in terms of any accessories that I have kind of eye color, my'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'hairstyle, anything that might be useful to the AI model and that you want to be more specific about. For the image model, we\'re going to predominantly be using Nano Banana Pro for this project. In my view, currently the best AI image'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'models on the market are Nano Banana Pro and GPT Image 2. I would veer more towards GPT image for photoreal outputs. But as we\'re going for something a lot more stylized here, I would point you'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'guys towards Nano Banana Pro. We also want to make sure that we\'re generating at at least 2K resolution. And it might be helpful to have a batch size of at least two so you can kind of have a'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'selection to pick from. So using this exact workflow, I got loads of great results, but this here was my personal favorite. I felt that it would fit the vibe of the show that I was looking to create, which was primarily a comedy.'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'But honestly, there are just so many amazing cartoon styles out here. There is really no right answer. It\'s really up to you to decide what type of vibe that you\'re going for. It can be'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'something a lot more detailed like this, or it could be something a lot more kind of minimal in line with this kind of design. Now, once you\'ve settled on your specific style, you want to go ahead'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'hover over the image and then click on this icon here so that you\'re using it as a reference. And the next and incredibly important step is to build up a character sheet. So you can see that'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'I\'ve dropped in this prompt framework here. Now the only part of this that you guys need to go ahead and modify is this opening section here. I still want you to leave in show the same bearded man,'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the same woman, boy, girl, whatever in the same art style with a neutral expression. Also useful to ask for the arms to be relaxed and to the character\'s side. We just want this to'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'be very neutral in terms of expression and pose as well. You can also use this stage of creating a character sheet to make slight edit tweaks to your initial image. You can see here, for example,'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'I\'ve said change to a healthy Caucasian skin tone. That\'s because some of the initial generations I was getting, I looked really quite tanned. And trust me, we don\'t get that much sun here in the UK. So, I wanted to keep it more'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'realistic as to how I would actually look as a cartoon character. And you can see here I\'ve then reinforced a little bit more about the description of my character. So again, accessories, hair color and style and clothing and things'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'like that. Particularly important for this example here because in the reference we\'re using, you can\'t see what trousers or trainers I\'m wearing. So if we don\'t give that information to Nano Banana, it\'s just going to kind of'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'guess and you might not get the result that you\'re after. So once you\'ve added those minor tweaks to this prompt framework, you can go ahead and click generate. And you\'re going to end up getting something that looks a little bit like this. Now, we\'ll use this later'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'on when we\'re generating our images and videos to give the AI models an understanding of what each character looks like from different views. Success with generative AI is all about'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'providing the models as much context as we possibly can. And that\'s why character sheets are so powerful. Any details that we don\'t provide to AI image or video models, they have to make'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'up. And that\'s why a lot of users end up getting frustrated. They don\'t get the results that they want and they just complain that they\'re wasting their credits. This is one route for solving that problem. Now, let me show you how'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you can actually create new characters using this one here as a reference. So, I\'m going to remove the current image reference that we have here. And I\'m instead going to reference this'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'character sheet that we just built. And I\'m going to remove the show the same bearded man. And we\'re going to say a grumpy cat. I\'m also going to get rid of the neutral expression because we want to convey that the cat is not a happy'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'character. We can remove this entire description here and I\'m just going to say he has a red collar. We\'re going to keep this really quite simple. We do want to make sure, like I said before,'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'that we\'re using Nano Banana Pro to build this out. 2K resolution. And let\'s go ahead and build a batch of four here. I\'m going to send this off by hitting generate. And just like that, we have back our new character in the same art'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'style as our reference image. And this is why it\'s so important to get your style locked in early on because it influences everything that comes after it. Honestly, they\'re all looking great,'

