[09:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'section. Just keeps things nice and organized. To access that, you just want to go up to the top right hand corner, click into assets, and then click on the favorites tab. You can see a bunch of images which I\'ve favored here. You can'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'see I also built up a couple of different characters. We\'ve got this angry looking pigeon here. And then we have this pink female monster as well. All of them have that consistent art'

[09:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'style, which is incredibly important if we don\'t want to kind of break the illusion. So, this first section here is all about locking in your style and then building up a selection of character reference sheets. All of this prep work'

[09:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is what\'s going to give you more control over your end result. And something else that\'s really important for cartoons is location consistency. And that\'s because a lot of these types of shows will use recurring locations. And so it\'s really'

[09:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'important that the logic holds up and that they feel consistent or you just end up losing your audience. So we can actually go about developing our locations in a very similar way to how'

[10:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'we built up our alternative characters. So, we first want to go ahead and reference our character reference sheet. And I\'m just going to drop in a super simple prompt here. We\'re going to say'

[10:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'in the same art style without showing any characters, show a cozy living room, comfy couch, and a big TV. And we get a result something like this. And this becomes our key visual for this specific'

[10:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'location. And now what we want to go ahead and do is generate multiple views of the same location. So we\'ll go ahead and click on the reference icon here. And now we\'re going to use this prompt'

[10:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'framework. The only bit you guys need to worry about is this area here, the different views. And essentially what I want you to do is think about where you would potentially show your characters sitting or standing in this location.'

[10:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'For example, for view one, I\'m going to say the sofa seat. For view two, I\'m going to say aerial view of the sofa where the character could be laying down. So, it\'s shot from above. View three, we\'re going to do the window'

[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'looking out to quiet suburbs. And view four, aerial view of the rug where the character could again be laying down. Let\'s say if he\'s having some kind of difficult day and he\'s decided to just lay down on the floor on the rug. And'

[11:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you\'ll end up getting a result something like this where we have these four different views which are completely empty which we can then place our characters into and we can use these multiple times. That\'s going to allow us'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to lock in that sense of consistency. I think the kind of family living room and particularly the sofa is a great example of this. If we think about shows like Family Guy or The Simpsons, a lot of'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'action happens around that kind of family ccentric area. But again, by taking all of these steps, it\'s just giving you as the creator much more control over your end result. You\'re now'

[12:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'going to be able to block out your scenes as you see fit, rather than just kind of generating them from scratch all of the time. We\'re always referencing these repeatable assets. So, let me just go ahead and give you guys a good'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'example of this. First of all, we\'re going to once again reference the character sheet for our main character. Then I\'m also going to go ahead and reference the location sheet which we just generated as well. So, what we can go ahead and do is we can type out show'

[12:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and then if we hit app on our keyboard, it\'s going to allow us to tag our image references. So, we want to select image one, which is our character reference sheet. And then we can say sat on the sofa from view one shown in. And then'

[12:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'we\'ll go ahead and we\'ll tag our location reference sheet. And that\'s why it\'s important that you guys use the prompt framework that I\'m going to supply you because it allows you to reference specific views. We\'re saying'

[13:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'that we want to show our main character sat on the sofa in view one. And using this method, we get a result exactly like this. And what\'s great is that we could have placed any of our characters'

[13:13] [scene:talk]
